/* procedure: "_SYS_STATISTICS"."ALERT_CHECK_DEPRECATED_FEATURE_USAGE"  variable: CALL_COUNT_LAST_INTERVAL line: 17 col: 103 (at pos 1512) */
select COMPONENT_NAME, FEATURE_NAME, CALL_COUNT, OBJECT_COUNT, IS_DEPRECATED,
       case
           when CALL_COUNT is null then 0
           when LAST_CALL_COUNT is null then CALL_COUNT
           else (CALL_COUNT - LAST_CALL_COUNT)
       end as DELTA_CALL_COUNT,
       case
           when OBJECT_COUNT is null then 0
           when LAST_OBJECT_COUNT is null then OBJECT_COUNT
           else (OBJECT_COUNT - LAST_OBJECT_COUNT)
       end as DELTA_OBJECT_COUNT
from _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_103_check_deprecated_feature_usage
left outer join
  (select last_COMPONENT_NAME, last_FEATURE_NAME, last_CALL_COUNT, last_OBJECT_COUNT, last_IS_DEPRECATED
   from _SYS_STATISTICS.HELPER_ALERT_CHECK_DEPRECATED_FEATURE_USAGE_LASTVALUES) on COMPONENT_NAME = last_COMPONENT_NAME
and FEATURE_NAME = last_FEATURE_NAME

/* procedure: "_SYS_STATISTICS"."ALERT_MON_PART_TABLE_SIZE_HOST_TOTAL_MEM"  variable: TABLES line: 21 col: 106 (at pos 1800) */
select top 100 t0.host || '.' || t0.port || '.' || t1.schema_name || '.' || t1.table_name || '.' || t1.part_id index_id, t0.host, t0.port, t1.schema_name, t1.table_name, t1.part_id,
               round(t1.memory_size_in_main / t0.effective_allocation_limit * 100, 0) main_mem_usage_perc,
               round(t1.memory_size_in_total / t0.effective_allocation_limit * 100, 0) total_mem_usage_perc, t1.memory_size_in_main, t1.memory_size_in_total,
               t0.effective_allocation_limit
from _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_40_service_memory t0, _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_40_cs_tables t1
where t0.host=t1.host
  and t0.port=t1.port
order by total_mem_usage_perc desc

Recommendation from SAP Note 2000002

This procedure is used to for statistics server alert 40 ("Total memory usage of column-store tables"). Runtimes up to 10 seconds for large systems are normal and acceptable. In rare cases it can be helpful to reduce the execution frequency. See SAP Note 2147247 for more information about the SAP HANA statistics servers in general and statistics server alerts in particular.

cc8c76c98e842c0db137e2a03895f2bc

SQL Text:

SELECT M.YEAR, M.MONTH, M.GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, M.MAX_SUM_OVER_APP_INSTANCE, H.VERSION
FROM
  (SELECT GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, YEAR, MONTH, MAX(MEASURE_TIME) AS LATEST_MEASURE_TIME,
          SUM(VALUE) MAX_SUM_OVER_APP_INSTANCE
   FROM
     (SELECT GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, APPLICATION_INSTANCE_ID, YEAR, MONTH, MAX(MEASURE_TIME) AS MEASURE_TIME,
             SUM(VALUE) VALUE
      FROM
        (SELECT GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, APPLICATION_INSTANCE_ID, YEAR(MEASURE_TIME) YEAR,
                                                                                 MONTH(MEASURE_TIME) MONTH,
                                                                                                     MEASURE_TIME,
                                                                                                     MAX(VALUE) AS VALUE,
                                                                                                     ROW_NUMBER() OVER(PARTITION BY GLAS_APPLICATION_ID,

                                                                                                                    APPLICATION_INSTANCE_ID,
                                                                                                                    YEAR(MEASURE_TIME),
                                                                                                                    MONTH(MEASURE_TIME)
                                                                                                                       ORDER BY MAX(VALUE) DESC, MEASURE_TIME DESC) ROW_NUM
         FROM LICENSE_MEASUREMENTS_
         WHERE GLAS_APPLICATION_ID NOT IN ('000670', '000675')
         GROUP BY GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, APPLICATION_INSTANCE_ID, YEAR(MEASURE_TIME), MONTH(MEASURE_TIME),
                  MEASURE_TIME)
      WHERE ROW_NUM = 1
      GROUP BY GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, APPLICATION_INSTANCE_ID, YEAR, MONTH)
   GROUP BY GLAS_APPLICATION_ID, YEAR, MONTH) M
LEFT JOIN
  (SELECT H1.INSTALL_TIME TIME_FROM, IFNULL(H2.INSTALL_TIME,
                                       CURRENT_TIMESTAMP) TIME_UTILL, H1.VERSION
   FROM
     (SELECT *, ROW_NUMBER() OVER(
                                  ORDER BY INSTALL_TIME ASC) ROW_NUM
      FROM SYS.M_DATABASE_HISTORY) H1
   LEFT JOIN
     (SELECT *, ROW_NUMBER() OVER(
                                  ORDER BY INSTALL_TIME ASC) ROW_NUM
      FROM SYS.M_DATABASE_HISTORY) H2 ON H1.ROW_NUM = H2.ROW_NUM - 1) H ON H.TIME_FROM <= M.LATEST_MEASURE_TIME
AND M.LATEST_MEASURE_TIME < H.TIME_UTILL
ORDER BY M.YEAR, M.MONTH, M.GLAS_APPLICATION_ID

/* procedure: "_SYS_STATISTICS"."ALERT_PRODUCT_PERCENTAGE_USAGE"  variable: ITEMS line: 17 col: 104 (at pos 1506) */
select product_usage, product_limit,
       map(product_limit, 0, 100, product_usage/product_limit*100) as product_usage_percentage, allocation_limit
from
  (select ifnull(sum(instance_total_memory_used_size)/(1024*1024*1024), 0) as product_usage, ifnull(max(product_limit),

                                                                                               0) as product_limit,
          ifnull(sum(allocation_limit)/(1024*1024*1024), 0) as allocation_limit
   from _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_44_resource_utilization ru, _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_44_host_configuration hc,
        _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_44_license
   where ru.host = hc.host
     and hc.indexserver_actual_role in ('MASTER','SLAVE'))

/* procedure: "_SYS_STATISTICS"."ALERT_MON_PART_TABLE_SIZE_HOST_MAIN_MEM"  variable: TABLES line: 21 col: 106 (at pos 1799) */
select top 100 t0.host || '.' || t0.port || '.' || t1.schema_name || '.' || t1.table_name || '.' || t1.part_id index_id, t0.host, t0.port, t1.schema_name, t1.table_name, t1.part_id,
               round(t1.memory_size_in_main / t0.effective_allocation_limit * 100, 0) main_mem_usage_perc,
               round(t1.memory_size_in_total / t0.effective_allocation_limit * 100, 0) total_mem_usage_perc, t1.memory_size_in_main, t1.memory_size_in_total,
               t0.effective_allocation_limit

where t0.host=t1.host
  and t0.port=t1.port
order by main_mem_usage_perc desc

Recommendation from SAP Note 2000002

A particularly high thread activity can be observed in systems where CPU workload management (in particular based on parameter default_statement_concurrency_limit) isn't properly set up, a high number of parallel threads is used and contention on IniFileLock (SAP Note 1999998) happens. In this case see SAP Notes 2222250 and 2600030 and make sure that a reasonably small value for default_statement_concurrency_limit is set.

With SAP HANA >= 2.00.041 the calculation of values for memory related columns (*MEMORY_SIZE*) in monitoring views M_CS_ALL_COLUMNS, M_CS_COLUMNS and M_CS_TABLES also considers columns that are currently not loaded (fix for ssue number 198542). This can result in overhead in terms of CPU consumption, JobWorker utilization and runtime when memory related columns are accessed in these monitoring views. Among others the following statistics server actions can suffer:

  • ID 20: Alert_Column_Tables_Size_Growth (statement hash 1f989f4acd844d502ccd445f69f5ea02, d3759ce6047b78f61d5fc3be392d0336)
  • ID 29: Alert_Delta_Mem_Merge_Dog (statement hashes 38a8e11286f7309f2715c07c270a473b)
  • ID 40: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Total_Mem (statement hash 430c496e0fe15c0353c80de1c72caab1)
  • ID 45: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Main_Mem (statement hash ba81a383d98a296d2e44e04278ccb770)
  • ID 5007: Collector_Host_Column_Tables_Part_Size (statement hash c6edbab2e426f7e83b156ed06ccdf6bb)

Also accesses in context of SAPHostAgent (user SAPDBCTRL) like hashes 1964c8ab878cde5f306d9f605e3b94ed or f1b12a80a3eb489df86f5e25097725db can be affected.

Avoid reading memory information from these monitoring views on a regular basis.

In order to limit the load spikes / CPU consumption introduced by the statistics server (SAP Note 2147247) you can set up a workload class with a maximum thread limit <max_threads> (SAP Note 2222250):

CREATE WORKLOAD CLASS "EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'PRIORITY' = '0',
'TOTAL STATEMENT THREAD LIMIT' = '<max_threads>', 'TOTAL STATEMENT MEMORY LIMIT' = '100';
CREATE WORKLOAD MAPPING "EssUserMapping" WORKLOAD CLASS 
"EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'USER NAME' = '_SYS_STATISTICS';

Issue number 266068 exists to minimize the CPU overhead in the future.

from _SYS_STATISTICS.SOURCE_COLLECTOR_5057_SERVICE_THREAD_CALLSTACKS STC
join _SYS_STATISTICS.SOURCE_COLLECTOR_5057_SERVICE_THREADS ST on STC.host = ST.host
and STC.port=ST.port
and STC.thread_id = ST.thread_id
where ST.connection_id != current_connection
  and STC.is_active = 'TRUE'
order by STC.thread_id, STC.frame_level

Recommendation from SAP Note 2000002

This insert populates the call stack history table HOST_SERVICE_THREAD_CALLSTACK_BASE that can e.g. be evaluated via SQL: "HANA_Threads_Callstacks_History" (SAP Note 1969700). Historic call stacks are helpful for troubleshooting purposes and so it is usually acceptable that this statement generates some load. See SAP Note 2313619 for more information related to SAP HANA call stacks.

                                           t2.allocation_limit) * 100 memory_size_in_delta_percent

Recommendation from SAP Note 2000002

A particularly high thread activity can be observed in systems where CPU workload management (in particular based on parameter default_statement_concurrency_limit) isn't properly set up, a high number of parallel threads is used and contention on IniFileLock (SAP Note 1999998) happens. In this case see SAP Notes 2222250 and 2600030 and make sure that a reasonably small value for default_statement_concurrency_limit is set.

With SAP HANA >= 2.00.041 the calculation of values for memory related columns (*MEMORY_SIZE*) in monitoring views M_CS_ALL_COLUMNS, M_CS_COLUMNS and M_CS_TABLES also considers columns that are currently not loaded (fix for ssue number 198542). This can result in overhead in terms of CPU consumption, JobWorker utilization and runtime when memory related columns are accessed in these monitoring views. Among others the following statistics server actions can suffer:

  • ID 20: Alert_Column_Tables_Size_Growth (statement hash 1f989f4acd844d502ccd445f69f5ea02, d3759ce6047b78f61d5fc3be392d0336)
  • ID 29: Alert_Delta_Mem_Merge_Dog (statement hashes 38a8e11286f7309f2715c07c270a473b)
  • ID 40: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Total_Mem (statement hash 430c496e0fe15c0353c80de1c72caab1)
  • ID 45: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Main_Mem (statement hash ba81a383d98a296d2e44e04278ccb770)
  • ID 5007: Collector_Host_Column_Tables_Part_Size (statement hash c6edbab2e426f7e83b156ed06ccdf6bb)

Also accesses in context of SAPHostAgent (user SAPDBCTRL) like hashes 1964c8ab878cde5f306d9f605e3b94ed or f1b12a80a3eb489df86f5e25097725db can be affected.

Avoid reading memory information from these monitoring views on a regular basis.

In order to limit the load spikes / CPU consumption introduced by the statistics server (SAP Note 2147247) you can set up a workload class with a maximum thread limit <max_threads> (SAP Note 2222250):

CREATE WORKLOAD CLASS "EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'PRIORITY' = '0',
'TOTAL STATEMENT THREAD LIMIT' = '<max_threads>', 'TOTAL STATEMENT MEMORY LIMIT' = '100';
CREATE WORKLOAD MAPPING "EssUserMapping" WORKLOAD CLASS 
"EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'USER NAME' = '_SYS_STATISTICS';

Issue number 266068 exists to minimize the CPU overhead in the future.

/* procedure: "_SYS_STATISTICS"."ALERT_COLUMN_TABLES_SIZE_GROWTH"  variable: BASE_TABLES line: 21 col: 104 (at pos 1800) */
select top 100 "SCHEMA_NAME" || '.' || "TABLE_NAME" "SCHEMA_TABLE_NAME", "SCHEMA_NAME", "TABLE_NAME",
               "TMP_SUM_MEMORY_SIZE_IN_TOTAL" "SUM_MEMORY_SIZE_IN_TOTAL", "TMP_SUM_RECORD_COUNT" "SUM_RECORD_COUNT", "PART_COUNT"
from
  (select "SCHEMA_NAME", "TABLE_NAME", sum("MEMORY_SIZE_IN_TOTAL") "TMP_SUM_MEMORY_SIZE_IN_TOTAL",
          sum("RECORD_COUNT") "TMP_SUM_RECORD_COUNT", count (*) "PART_COUNT"
   from _SYS_STATISTICS.source_alert_20_cs_tables
   where schema_name||'.'||table_name not in
       (select schema_name||'.'||table_name
        from _SYS_STATISTICS.statistics_exclude_tables
        where alert_id = CAST(20 AS INT) )
     and schema_name not in
       (select schema_name
        from _SYS_STATISTICS.statistics_exclude_tables
        where table_name is null
          and alert_id = CAST(20 AS INT) )
   group by "SCHEMA_NAME", "TABLE_NAME")
where "TMP_SUM_MEMORY_SIZE_IN_TOTAL" > 0
order by sum_record_count desc

Recommendation from SAP Note 2000002

A particularly high thread activity can be observed in systems where CPU workload management (in particular based on parameter default_statement_concurrency_limit) isn't properly set up, a high number of parallel threads is used and contention on IniFileLock (SAP Note 1999998) happens. In this case see SAP Notes 2222250 and 2600030 and make sure that a reasonably small value for default_statement_concurrency_limit is set.

With SAP HANA >= 2.00.041 the calculation of values for memory related columns (*MEMORY_SIZE*) in monitoring views M_CS_ALL_COLUMNS, M_CS_COLUMNS and M_CS_TABLES also considers columns that are currently not loaded (fix for ssue number 198542). This can result in overhead in terms of CPU consumption, JobWorker utilization and runtime when memory related columns are accessed in these monitoring views. Among others the following statistics server actions can suffer:

  • ID 20: Alert_Column_Tables_Size_Growth (statement hash 1f989f4acd844d502ccd445f69f5ea02, d3759ce6047b78f61d5fc3be392d0336)
  • ID 29: Alert_Delta_Mem_Merge_Dog (statement hashes 38a8e11286f7309f2715c07c270a473b)
  • ID 40: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Total_Mem (statement hash 430c496e0fe15c0353c80de1c72caab1)
  • ID 45: Alert_Mon_Part_Table_Size_Host_Main_Mem (statement hash ba81a383d98a296d2e44e04278ccb770)
  • ID 5007: Collector_Host_Column_Tables_Part_Size (statement hash c6edbab2e426f7e83b156ed06ccdf6bb)

Also accesses in context of SAPHostAgent (user SAPDBCTRL) like hashes 1964c8ab878cde5f306d9f605e3b94ed or f1b12a80a3eb489df86f5e25097725db can be affected.

Avoid reading memory information from these monitoring views on a regular basis.

In order to limit the load spikes / CPU consumption introduced by the statistics server (SAP Note 2147247) you can set up a workload class with a maximum thread limit <max_threads> (SAP Note 2222250):

CREATE WORKLOAD CLASS "EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'PRIORITY' = '0',
'TOTAL STATEMENT THREAD LIMIT' = '<max_threads>', 'TOTAL STATEMENT MEMORY LIMIT' = '100';
CREATE WORKLOAD MAPPING "EssUserMapping" WORKLOAD CLASS 
"EssConcurrencyClass" SET 'USER NAME' = '_SYS_STATISTICS';

Issue number 266068 exists to minimize the CPU overhead in the future.

select p.host || ':' || p.port || ':' || c.logical_connection_id || ':' || map(p.statement_id,
                                                                             null,
                                                                             '',
                                                                             p.statement_id) index_id, p.host, p.port, c.logical_connection_id, p.statement_id,
       map(c.client_host, null, '', c.client_host) client_host, c.client_pid, p.statement_string,
       seconds_between(p.last_executed_time, current_timestamp) runtime, seconds_between(p.last_action_time,

                                                                           current_timestamp) idle_time,
       p.start_mvcc_timestamp, c.connection_status, p.statement_status,
       map(application.application, null, '', application.application) application,
       map(applicationsource.applicationsource, null, '', applicationsource.applicationsource) applicationsource,
       map(applicationversion.applicationversion, null, '', applicationversion.applicationversion) applicationversion,
       map(applicationuser.applicationuser, null, '', applicationuser.applicationuser) applicationuser, PLANCACHE.STATEMENT_HASH
FROM SYS.M_ACTIVE_STATEMENTS P
LEFT OUTER JOIN m_sql_plan_cache PLANCACHE ON P.HOST = PLANCACHE.HOST
AND P.PORT = PLANCACHE.PORT
AND P.PLAN_ID = PLANCACHE.PLAN_ID , SYS.M_CONNECTIONS C
LEFT OUTER JOIN
  (SELECT VALUE APPLICATION, HOST, PORT, CONNECTION_ID
   FROM SYS.M_SESSION_CONTEXT
   WHERE KEY = 'APPLICATION' ) APPLICATION ON C.HOST = APPLICATION.HOST
AND C.PORT = APPLICATION.PORT
AND C.CONNECTION_ID = APPLICATION.CONNECTION_ID
LEFT OUTER JOIN
  (SELECT VALUE APPLICATIONSOURCE, HOST, PORT, CONNECTION_ID
   FROM SYS.M_SESSION_CONTEXT
   WHERE KEY = 'APPLICATIONSOURCE' ) APPLICATIONSOURCE ON C.HOST = APPLICATIONSOURCE.HOST
AND C.PORT = APPLICATIONSOURCE.PORT
AND C.CONNECTION_ID = APPLICATIONSOURCE.CONNECTION_ID
LEFT OUTER JOIN
  (SELECT VALUE APPLICATIONVERSION, HOST, PORT, CONNECTION_ID
   FROM SYS.M_SESSION_CONTEXT
   WHERE KEY = 'APPLICATIONVERSION' ) APPLICATIONVERSION ON C.HOST = APPLICATIONVERSION.HOST
AND C.PORT = APPLICATIONVERSION.PORT
AND C.CONNECTION_ID = APPLICATIONVERSION.CONNECTION_ID
LEFT OUTER JOIN
  (SELECT VALUE APPLICATIONUSER, HOST, PORT, CONNECTION_ID
   FROM SYS.M_SESSION_CONTEXT
   WHERE KEY = 'APPLICATIONUSER' ) APPLICATIONUSER ON C.HOST = APPLICATIONUSER.HOST
AND C.PORT = APPLICATIONUSER.PORT
AND C.CONNECTION_ID = APPLICATIONUSER.CONNECTION_ID
where P.HOST = C.HOST
  and P.PORT = C.PORT
  and C.CONNECTION_ID=P.CONNECTION_ID
  and C.CONNECTION_ID > 0
  AND P.LAST_ACTION_TIME IS NOT NULL
  AND P.LAST_EXECUTED_TIME IS NOT NULL
  AND P.STATEMENT_STATUS<>'NONE'
  AND P.STATEMENT_STATUS<>'ACTIVE'
  AND seconds_between(P.LAST_EXECUTED_TIME, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP) > 0
ORDER BY P.START_MVCC_TIMESTAMP
